===Consecutive wins===
[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 46 - Terry Bradshaw (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|The [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Steelers]] defeated the [[Los Angeles Rams|Rams]] in [[Super Bowl XIV]] to win an unprecedented four championships in six years.]]

Eight franchises have won consecutive Super Bowls, one of which (Pittsburgh) has accomplished it twice:

* [[Green Bay Packers]] (Super Bowls [[Super Bowl I|I]] and [[Super Bowl II|II]])
* [[Miami Dolphins]] ([[Super Bowl VII|VII]] and [[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]])
* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (twice: [[Super Bowl IX|IX]] and [[Super Bowl X|X]]; [[Super Bowl XIII|XIII]] and [[Super Bowl XIV|XIV]])
* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ([[Super Bowl XXIII|XXIII]] and [[Super Bowl XXIV|XXIV]])
* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ([[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]] and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]])
* [[Denver Broncos]] ([[Super Bowl XXXII|XXXII]] and [[Super Bowl XXXIII|XXXIII]])<ref group=n name=BroncosStreaks />
* [[New England Patriots]] ([[Super Bowl XXXVIII|XXXVIII]] and [[Super Bowl XXXIX|XXXIX]])
* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ([[Super Bowl LVII|LVII]] and [[Super Bowl LVIII|LVIII]])

Although no franchise to date has won three Super Bowls in a row, several have had eras of sustained success, nearly accomplishing a [[three-peat]]:

* The [[Green Bay Packers]] won the first two Super Bowls, and also won the [[1965 NFL Championship Game|NFL Championship Game the preceding year]]. If the Super Bowl had been instituted that year, the Packers would have qualified and faced the Buffalo Bills of the AFL.
* The [[Miami Dolphins]] appeared in three consecutive Super Bowls ([[Super Bowl VI|VI]], [[Super Bowl VII|VII]], and [[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]])&nbsp;– winning the last two.
* The [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] won two consecutive Super Bowls ([[Super Bowl IX|IX]] and [[Super Bowl X|X]]); the following season they were eliminated in the [[1976–77 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship: Oakland Raiders 24, Pittsburgh Steelers 7|AFC Championship Game]] by the eventual [[Super Bowl XI]] champion [[1976 Oakland Raiders season|Oakland Raiders]]. They also won two more consecutive Super Bowls ([[Super Bowl XIII|XIII]] and [[Super Bowl XIV|XIV]]) for four titles in six seasons.
* The [[San Francisco 49ers]] won two consecutive Super Bowls ([[Super Bowl XXIII|XXIII]] and [[Super Bowl XXIV|XXIV]]); the following season they were eliminated in the [[1990–91 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship: New York Giants 15, San Francisco 49ers 13|NFC Championship Game]] by the eventual [[Super Bowl XXV]] champion [[1990 New York Giants season|New York Giants]].
* The [[Dallas Cowboys]] won two consecutive Super Bowls ([[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]] and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]]); the following season they were eliminated in the [[1994–95 NFL playoffs#NFC Championship: San Francisco 49ers 38, Dallas Cowboys 28|NFC Championship Game]] by the eventual [[Super Bowl XXIX]] champion [[1994 San Francisco 49ers season|San Francisco 49ers]]. The [[1995 Dallas Cowboys season|Cowboys]] won [[Super Bowl XXX]] the following year for three titles in four seasons, and thus were two wins away from four consecutive Super Bowl titles.
* The [[New England Patriots]] won Super Bowls [[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]], [[Super Bowl LI|LI]], and [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]] for three titles in five seasons. They also appeared in and lost [[Super Bowl LII]] to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]] following the 2017 season, giving them four Super Bowl appearances in five years and putting them one win away from three consecutive Super Bowl titles. In the intervening year, they were eliminated in the [[2015–16 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 20, New England Patriots 18|AFC Championship Game]] by the eventual [[Super Bowl 50]] champion [[2015 Denver Broncos season|Denver Broncos]].
* The [[Kansas City Chiefs]] made four Super Bowls in five years, winning [[Super Bowl LIV|LIV]], [[Super Bowl LVII|LVII]], and [[Super Bowl LVIII|LVIII]], while losing [[Super Bowl LV|LV]]. In the intervening year, they lost the [[2021 AFC Championship Game]] to the [[2021 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]] in overtime, coming one win short of five consecutive appearances. Additionally, in the year prior to their victory in LIV, the Chiefs lost the [[2018 AFC Championship Game]] to the [[2018 New England Patriots season|New England Patriots]] in overtime, resulting in being two wins short of six consecutive appearances.

===Consecutive losses===
Three franchises have lost consecutive Super Bowls:
* [[Buffalo Bills]] (4) (Super Bowls [[Super Bowl XXV|XXV]], [[Super Bowl XXVI|XXVI]], [[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]], and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]]) – The only team to appear in four straight Super Bowls; they lost in all four appearances.
* [[Minnesota Vikings]] (2) ([[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]] and [[Super Bowl IX|IX]]) – They also lost [[Super Bowl XI]], and were [[1975–76 NFL playoffs#NFC: Dallas Cowboys 17, Minnesota Vikings 14|knocked out of the 1975–76 playoffs]] by the eventual [[Super Bowl X]] losers, [[1975 Dallas Cowboys season|the Dallas Cowboys]], for three losses in four seasons.
* [[Denver Broncos]] (2) ([[Super Bowl XXI|XXI]] and [[Super Bowl XXII|XXII]]) – They also lost [[Super Bowl XXIV]], but did not qualify for the [[1988–89 NFL playoffs|1988–89 playoffs]] for [[Super Bowl XXIII]] for three losses in four seasons.<ref group=n name=BroncosStreaks />

===Consecutive appearances===
The [[Buffalo Bills]] have the most consecutive appearances with four from 1990 to 1993. The [[Miami Dolphins]] (1971–1973) and [[New England Patriots]] (2016–2018) are the only other teams to have at least three consecutive appearances. All three teams with three or more consecutive Super Bowl appearances are in the [[AFC East]] division. Including those three, 11 teams have at least two consecutive appearances. The [[Dallas Cowboys]] are the only team with three separate streaks (1970–1971, 1977–1978, and 1992–1993). The [[Green Bay Packers]], [[Pittsburgh Steelers]], [[Denver Broncos]],<ref group=n name=BroncosStreaks /> and New England Patriots have each had two separate consecutive appearances. The [[Kansas City Chiefs]] are the most recent team to appear in consecutive Super Bowls, playing in [[Super Bowl LVII]] and [[Super Bowl LVIII]]. The full listing of teams with consecutive appearances is below in order of first occurrence; winning games are in '''bold''':
* [[Green Bay Packers]] (twice: Super Bowls [[Super Bowl I|'''I''']] and [[Super Bowl II|'''II''']]; [[Super Bowl XXXI|'''XXXI''']] and [[Super Bowl XXXII|XXXII]])
* [[Dallas Cowboys]] (thrice: [[Super Bowl V|V]] and [[Super Bowl VI|'''VI''']]; [[Super Bowl XII|'''XII''']] and [[Super Bowl XIII|XIII]]; [[Super Bowl XXVII|'''XXVII''']] and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|'''XXVIII''']])
* [[Miami Dolphins]] ([[Super Bowl VI|VI]], [[Super Bowl VII|'''VII''']], and [[Super Bowl VIII|'''VIII''']])
* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ([[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]] and [[Super Bowl IX|IX]])
* [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] (twice: [[Super Bowl IX|'''IX''']] and [[Super Bowl X|'''X''']]; [[Super Bowl XIII|'''XIII''']] and [[Super Bowl XIV|'''XIV''']])
* [[Washington Redskins]] ([[Super Bowl XVII|'''XVII''']] and [[Super Bowl XVIII|XVIII]])
* [[Denver Broncos]] (twice: [[Super Bowl XXI|XXI]] and [[Super Bowl XXII|XXII]]; [[Super Bowl XXXII|'''XXXII''']] and [[Super Bowl XXXIII|'''XXXIII''']]){{#tag:ref|The [[Denver Broncos|Broncos]] are the only [[NFL team]] with both consecutive wins and consecutive losses at the [[Super Bowl]].|group=n|name=BroncosStreaks}}
* [[San Francisco 49ers]] ([[Super Bowl XXIII|'''XXIII''']] and [[Super Bowl XXIV|'''XXIV''']])
* [[Buffalo Bills]] ([[Super Bowl XXV|XXV]], [[Super Bowl XXVI|XXVI]], [[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]], and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]])
* [[New England Patriots]] (twice: [[Super Bowl XXXVIII|'''XXXVIII''']] and [[Super Bowl XXXIX|'''XXXIX''']]; [[Super Bowl LI|'''LI''']], [[Super Bowl LII|LII]], and [[Super Bowl LIII|'''LIII''']])
* [[Seattle Seahawks]] ([[Super Bowl XLVIII|'''XLVIII''']] and [[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]])
* [[Kansas City Chiefs]] (twice: [[Super Bowl LIV|'''LIV''']] and [[Super Bowl LV|LV]]; [[Super Bowl LVII|'''LVII''']] and [[Super Bowl LVIII|'''LVIII''']])

===Super Bowl rematches===
[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 27 - Dan Bunz (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|The [[San Francisco 49ers|49ers]] and the [[Cincinnati Bengals|Bengals]], who faced off in [[Super Bowl XVI]] (''pictured''), would play each other again in [[Super Bowl XXIII]].]]
The following teams have faced each other more than once in the Super Bowl:{{#tag:ref|The [[New York Jets]] and [[History of the Baltimore Colts|Baltimore]]/[[Indianapolis Colts]] ([[Super Bowl III]]) is the only [[Super Bowl]] matchup that cannot be repeated under the current playoff alignment, as the Colts have since been placed in the [[American Football Conference|AFC]] (at the time, along with all of the former [[American Football League|AFL]] teams, including the Jets) as part of the [[AFL–NFL merger]] in 1970. For the same reason, it is the only Super Bowl rematch that is capable of being played in the postseason outside of the Super Bowl.|group=n|name=ImpossibleRematch}}
* 3 times – [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ([[Super Bowl X|X]] and [[Super Bowl XIII|XIII]]) vs. [[Dallas Cowboys]] ([[Super Bowl XXX|XXX]]) ''see also [[Cowboys–Steelers rivalry]]''
* 2 times – [[Miami Dolphins]] ([[Super Bowl VII|VII]]) vs. [[Washington Redskins]] ([[Super Bowl XVII|XVII]])
* 2 times – [[San Francisco 49ers]] ([[Super Bowl XVI|XVI]] and [[Super Bowl XXIII|XXIII]]) vs. [[Cincinnati Bengals]]
* 2 times – [[Dallas Cowboys]] ([[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]] and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]]) vs. [[Buffalo Bills]]{{#tag:ref|The [[Dallas Cowboys]] and [[Buffalo Bills]] are the only NFL teams to face each other in consecutive [[Super Bowl]]s, [[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]] and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]].|group=n|name=ConsecutiveRematch}}
* 2 times – [[New York Giants]] ([[Super Bowl XLII|XLII]] and [[Super Bowl XLVI|XLVI]]) vs. [[New England Patriots]] ''see also [[Giants–Patriots rivalry]]''
* 2 times – New England Patriots ([[Super Bowl XXXIX|XXXIX]]) vs. [[Philadelphia Eagles]] ([[Super Bowl LII|LII]])
* 2 times – New England Patriots ([[Super Bowl XXXVI|XXXVI]] and [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]]) vs. [[Los Angeles Rams|St. Louis/Los Angeles Rams]]{{#tag:ref|This is the only rematch pairing in which one team has [[National Football League franchise moves and mergers|relocated]] in the interim. The Rams represented St. Louis in [[Super Bowl XXXVI]] and Los Angeles in [[Super Bowl LIII]].|group=n|name=Relocated}}
* 2 times – [[Kansas City Chiefs]] ([[Super Bowl LIV|LIV]] and [[Super Bowl LVIII|LVIII]]) vs. [[San Francisco 49ers]]

