[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 11 - Jim McMahon (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|The New England Patriots played their first championship game in [[Super Bowl XX]] (''pictured'') where they lost to the [[Chicago Bears|Bears]]. This is the most recent [[Super Bowl]] where both teams had their first Super Bowl appearance. The Patriots hold the record for most Super Bowl appearances (11) and are tied for both most wins (6, tied with the [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Steelers]]) and most losses (5, tied with the [[Denver Broncos|Broncos]]).]]<!--Deliberately not in the below section as it is more relevant in this one. It is placed below the table so that the width of the table isn't excessively shrunk.-->

===Teams with Super Bowl appearances but no victories===
Eight teams have appeared in the Super Bowl without ever winning. In descending order of number of appearances and then years since their last appearance, they are:
* [[Minnesota Vikings]] (4) – appeared in Super Bowls [[Super Bowl IV|IV]], [[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]], [[Super Bowl IX|IX]], and [[Super Bowl XI|XI]]; they won the [[1969 NFL Championship Game|NFL Championship]] in [[1969 NFL season|1969]], the last year before the [[AFL–NFL merger]], but failed to win [[Super Bowl IV|the subsequent Super Bowl]]. An NFL expansion team in [[1961 Minnesota Vikings season|1961]], they have no pre-Super Bowl league championships.
* [[Buffalo Bills]] (4) – [[Super Bowl XXV|XXV]], [[Super Bowl XXVI|XXVI]], [[Super Bowl XXVII|XXVII]], and [[Super Bowl XXVIII|XXVIII]]; in [[1964 AFL season|1964]] and [[1965 AFL season|1965]], they won the [[1964 American Football League Championship Game|last]] [[1965 American Football League Championship Game|two]] AFL Championships before the [[Super Bowl I|first Super Bowl]] in [[1966 AFL season|1966]].
* [[Cincinnati Bengals]] (3) – [[Super Bowl XVI|XVI]], [[Super Bowl XXIII|XXIII]], and [[Super Bowl LVI|LVI]]; an AFL expansion team in [[1968 Cincinnati Bengals season|1968]], they have no pre-Super Bowl league championships.
* [[Carolina Panthers]] (2) – [[Super Bowl XXXVIII|XXXVIII]] and [[Super Bowl 50|50]]; a post-merger expansion team, their first season was in [[1995 Carolina Panthers season|1995]].
* [[Atlanta Falcons]] (2) – [[Super Bowl XXXIII|XXXIII]] and [[Super Bowl LI|LI]]; an NFL expansion team in [[1966 Atlanta Falcons season|1966]], they have no pre-Super Bowl league championships.
* [[Los Angeles Chargers]] (1) – [[Super Bowl XXIX|XXIX]] as the [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]]; their only [[1963 American Football League Championship Game|AFL Championship]] was in [[1963 AFL season|1963]], also as the San Diego Chargers.
* [[Tennessee Titans]] (1) – [[Super Bowl XXXIV|XXXIV]]; they won the [[1960 American Football League Championship Game|first]] [[1961 American Football League Championship Game|two]] AFL Championships in [[1960 AFL season|1960]] and [[1961 AFL season|1961]] as the [[History of the Houston Oilers|Houston Oilers]].
* [[Arizona Cardinals]] (1) – [[Super Bowl XLIII|XLIII]]; they won two [[1947 NFL Championship Game|NFL Championship]]s, one in [[1925 NFL season|1925]] and then again in [[1947 NFL season|1947]], both as the [[History of the Chicago Cardinals|Chicago Cardinals]].

===Teams with no Super Bowl appearances or long active droughts===
[[File:1986 Jeno's Pizza - 37 - Joe Namath (cropped).jpg|upright|thumb|The [[New York Jets|Jets]]' most recent championship appearance was their victory over the [[Baltimore Colts|Colts]] in [[Super Bowl III]].]]
Four current teams have never reached the Super Bowl (shown in '''bold''' below). Two of them (Jacksonville and Houston) joined the NFL relatively recently, and there are an additional eight teams whose Super Bowl appearance droughts began prior to 2002 (the year Houston joined the NFL).  The other two teams that have never appeared in a Super Bowl (Cleveland and Detroit) both held [[List of NFL champions (1920–69)|NFL league championships]] prior to [[Super Bowl I]] in the [[1966 NFL season]].{{#tag:ref|[[Detroit]], [[Houston]], and [[Jacksonville]] have all hosted [[Super Bowl]]s, making [[Cleveland]] the only current NFL city that has neither hosted nor had its team play in a Super Bowl.|group=n|name=NFLCityNoSB}}  Teams are listed below according to the length of their current Super Bowl droughts (as of the end of the 2023 season, after Super Bowl LVIII):
* '''[[Cleveland Browns]]''', 58 years – NFL champions four times in [[1950 NFL Championship Game|1950]], [[1954 NFL Championship Game|1954]], [[1955 NFL Championship Game|1955]], and [[1964 NFL Championship Game|1964]]; appeared in seven other [[List of NFL champions (1920–1969)|NFL Championship Games]] in [[1951 NFL Championship Game|1951]], [[1952 NFL Championship Game|1952]], [[1953 NFL Championship Game|1953]], [[1957 NFL Championship Game|1957]], [[1965 NFL Championship Game|1965]], [[1968 NFL Championship Game|1968]], and [[1969 NFL Championship Game|1969]]; and appeared in three [[AFC Championship Game]]s in the [[1986–87 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 23, Cleveland Browns 20 (OT)|1986]], [[1987–88 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 38, Cleveland Browns 33|1987]], and [[1989–90 NFL playoffs#AFC: Denver Broncos 37, Cleveland Browns 21|1989 season]]s.<ref name=BrownsResults>{{Cite web |title= Cleveland Browns Franchise Encyclopedia |website= [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/ |access-date= August 27, 2009 |archive-date= October 18, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131018094523/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/cle/ |url-status= live }}</ref> The Browns are officially viewed as one continuous franchise that began in [[1946 Cleveland Browns season|1946]] as a member of the [[All-America Football Conference]], [[AAFC–NFL merger|joined the NFL]] in [[1950 Cleveland Browns season|1950]], suspended operations after [[1995 Cleveland Browns season|1995]], and resumed play in [[1999 Cleveland Browns season|1999]].<ref name=BrownsResults />{{#tag:ref|Although the 1995 Cleveland Browns became the 1996 Baltimore Ravens, the Browns' name, brand and history remained in Cleveland and was continued by the 1999 Cleveland Browns; the Ravens, for historical purposes, are considered a separate franchise.|group=n|name=ArtModell}}
* '''[[Detroit Lions]]''', 58 years – NFL champions four times in [[1935 NFL Championship Game|1935]], [[1952 NFL Championship Game|1952]], [[1953 NFL Championship Game|1953]], and [[1957 NFL Championship Game|1957]]; appeared in one other [[List of NFL champions (1920–1969)|NFL Championship Game]] in [[1954 NFL Championship Game|1954]]; and  appeared in two [[NFC Championship Game|NFC Championship Games]] in the [[1991–92 NFL playoffs#NFC: Washington Redskins 41, Detroit Lions 10|1991]] and [[2023 NFL season|2023 season]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Detroit Lions Franchise Encyclopedia |website= [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/det/ |access-date= August 27, 2009 |archive-date= October 4, 2020 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20201004011702/https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/det/ |url-status= live }}</ref>
* [[New York Jets]], 55 years – Won [[Super Bowl III]], [[1968 American Football League season|1968 season]]<ref>{{Cite web |last= Neumann |first= Thomas |title= Page 2's ultimate NFL power rankings, Nos. 21–32 |work= [[ESPN]] |publisher= [[The Walt Disney Company]] |date= September 17, 2008 |url= https://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story?page=nflrankings/21-32/080917 |access-date= September 7, 2009 |archive-date= February 7, 2009 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090207143055/http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/page2/story?page=nflrankings/21-32/080917 |url-status= live }}</ref>{{#tag:ref|The [[New York Jets|Jets]] and the [[Kansas City Chiefs|Chiefs]] are the only non-[[National Football League|NFL]] teams to win the [[Super Bowl]], both being members of the now-defunct [[American Football League|AFL]] at the time. The Jets have not appeared in the Super Bowl since joining the NFL following the [[AFL–NFL merger]] in 1970.|group=n|name=nonNFLSBChampions}} 
* [[Minnesota Vikings]], 47 years – Lost [[Super Bowl XI]], [[1976 NFL season|1976 season]]
* [[Miami Dolphins]], 39 years – Lost [[Super Bowl XIX]], [[1984 NFL season|1984 season]]
* [[Washington Commanders]], 32 years – Won [[Super Bowl XXVI]], [[1991 NFL season|1991 season]] (played as [[History of the Washington Football Team|Washington Redskins]])
* [[Buffalo Bills]], 30 years – Lost [[Super Bowl XXVIII]], [[1993 NFL season|1993 season]]
* [[Los Angeles Chargers]], 29 years – Lost [[Super Bowl XXIX]], [[1994 NFL season|1994 season]] (played as [[History of the San Diego Chargers|San Diego Chargers]])
* '''[[Jacksonville Jaguars]]''', 29 years – [[1995 Jacksonville Jaguars season|1995]] [[expansion team#National Football League|expansion team]]; three [[AFC Championship Game]] appearances in the [[1996–97 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 20, Jacksonville Jaguars 6|1996]], [[1999–2000 NFL playoffs#AFC: Tennessee Titans 33, Jacksonville Jaguars 14|1999]], and [[2017–18 NFL playoffs#AFC Championship Game: New England Patriots 24, Jacksonville Jaguars 20|2017 season]]s.<ref>{{Cite web |title= Jacksonville Jaguars Franchise Encyclopedia |website= [[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |url= https://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/ |access-date= August 27, 2009 |archive-date= January 15, 2016 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160115203217/http://www.pro-football-reference.com/teams/jax/ |url-status= live }}</ref>
* [[Dallas Cowboys]], 28 years – Won [[Super Bowl XXX]], [[1995 NFL season|1995 season]]
* [[Tennessee Titans]], 24 years – Lost [[Super Bowl XXXIV]], [[1999 NFL season|1999 season]]
* '''[[Houston Texans]]''', 22 years – [[2002 Houston Texans season|2002]] [[expansion team#National Football League|expansion team]]; [[NFL playoffs#Current playoff system|Divisional Round]] appearances in the [[2011–12 NFL playoffs#AFC: Baltimore Ravens 20, Houston Texans 13|2011]], [[2012–13 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 41, Houston Texans 28|2012]], [[2016–17 NFL playoffs#AFC: New England Patriots 34, Houston Texans 16|2016]], [[2019–20 NFL playoffs#AFC: Kansas City Chiefs 51, Houston Texans 31|2019]], and [[2023 NFL season|2023 season]]s. They are the only NFL team to never reach the Conference Championship round.

